1. Introduction
The Java Collections framework gives you many ways to store the same data — lists, sets, maps, queues — and they look interchangeable until you measure them. Behind each is a different data structure with different costs for each operation, and your course notes present those costs as Big-O tables: a HashMap lookup is constant time, a TreeMap lookup is logarithmic, and finding an item in a LinkedList is linear. The purpose of this lab is to prove those tables on a real machine.

You will not write the benchmark code by hand, and you will not copy any measured numbers into your report. Instead, you will give GitHub Copilot clear, precise instructions to build a program that measures the structures and prints the results as finished tables and CSV files. Two skills are being assessed: how well you instruct the assistant, and how well you understand the results — enough to predict them in advance and to judge whether what comes back is correct. Understanding is the part that Copilot cannot provide for you.

The lab’s central task is this. Using GitHub Copilot, you will write your own versions of the Java collections — your own list, your own hash map — and then compare them, operation by operation, against the native JDK 21 collections. You measure both your code and the JDK code on the same harness, at the same sizes, and you explain where your implementation matches the library’s time and space complexity and where it falls behind. Everything else in the lab — measuring the JDK structures first, scaling to a large workload — builds toward that comparison.

