3. Background you need (to judge whether the output is right)
3.1 Reading complexity off a curve
Plot the time an operation takes against the number of elements n. A horizontal line is constant time, O(1). A straight rising line is linear, O(n). A line that rises then flattens is logarithmic, O(log n). A line curving sharply upward is quadratic, O(n²). The shape is the empirical complexity, and your program will classify it for you — your job is to know whether its guess is believable.

3.2 Space versus real bytes
Every collection holding n items is O(n) in space, so the class alone says little. What differs is the bytes per element. An ArrayList packs items in one array, so the overhead is tiny; a HashMap wraps each entry in a node and keeps a bucket array with spare slots; a TreeMap gives each entry a node with child and colour pointers. Same O(n), very different real memory.

3.3 What makes a measurement honest
Four rules, and you must make sure your instruction to Copilot includes every one, then check the generated code obeys them. The JIT compiler only optimises code after thousands of runs, so the first runs are far too slow — warm up first and do not time the warmup. The compiler deletes a result you never use, so the program must add every result into a running total it prints at the end. The garbage collector can pause mid-measurement, so run several times and take the median. And generating or reading the data inside the timed region measures the data, not the operation — build the data first, time only the operation.

3.4 The structures you will measure
From the framework: the List family (ArrayList, LinkedList) and the double-ended queue ArrayDeque; the Set family (HashSet, LinkedHashSet, TreeSet); the Map family (HashMap, LinkedHashMap, TreeMap); and the heap-backed PriorityQueue. Your notes give the Big-O for each — that table is the prediction you are testing.

 

 

