Appendix A — How to instruct Copilot for this lab
A.1 What a good instruction contains
Before you type a prompt, make sure it names every one of these. A prompt missing any of them will produce a benchmark that lies:

the exact structures and operations to measure;
the sizes of n to test, written out;
that the data must be built before timing, with elements generated on the fly, never read from disk in a timed loop;
that it must warm up first and not time the warmup;
that every result must be added into a total it prints at the end, so nothing is optimised away;
the exact output you want: a console table and a named CSV file.
A.2 A worked example instruction
This is the kind of prompt that produces a trustworthy Part A program. Adapt it for the sets, the maps, and the priority queue.

Write a Java program that measures the time per operation of ArrayList,

LinkedList, and ArrayDeque. For each structure and for get(index),

add-at-end, add-at-front, and contains:

  - build the structure with n random Integers, generated on the fly,

    for n = 1_000, 10_000, 100_000, 1_000_000, 10_000_000;

  - run 1,000,000 operations as an untimed warm-up;

  - then time 1,000,000 operations with System.nanoTime();

  - add every result into a long 'sink' and print it at the end,

    so the JIT cannot delete the loop;

  - report nanoseconds per operation;

  - compute the ratio of ns/op between each size and the next, and from

    it print a guessed Big-O (about 1x -> O(1), about 2x -> O(n),

    small and shrinking -> O(log n));

  - print a neat table AND write the same rows to timeA.csv with a header.

Do not read any data from disk inside a timed loop.

A.3 Mistakes Copilot makes that you must catch
No warm-up, or it times the warm-up too — the first runs will look far slower than the truth.
It times the building of the structure instead of the operation — read the code and check what sits inside the timed block.
It never uses the result, so the JIT deletes the work and you get impossibly fast times — insist on the printed sink.
It shares one Random across everything or reads input in the loop — both distort the timing.
It forgets to write the CSV, or writes it without a header — you need the file to attach.
A.4 How to know the output is trustworthy
An O(1) operation’s ns/op should barely change as n grows; if it climbs steeply, something is wrong.
Run the program twice — the ns/op figures should be close; wild swings mean the garbage collector or warm-up is interfering.
Bytes-per-element should land in a sane range (tens of bytes for simple structures); a tiny or enormous figure means the measurement is off.
 

 

Appendix B — The in-memory LOBSTER-like data stream
Part C uses starter code, LobsterStream.java, supplied with this lab. It simulates a stream of limit-order-book events — the kind a real exchange feed (such as LOBSTER’s NASDAQ data) produces — and feeds them through Java collections, all in memory. This appendix explains how it works, what you complete, and how to run it.

B.1 What the LOBSTER dataset is
LOBSTER (Limit Order Book System for Efficient Reconstruction) is an academic data tool that rebuilds the complete limit order book of NASDAQ-listed stocks from the exchange’s raw message feed. It was created by Ruihong Huang and Tomas Polak in 2011 and has supplied high-frequency data to the research community since 2013. It takes NASDAQ’s Historical TotalView-ITCH feed — the timestamped record of every order submission, cancellation, and execution — and replays it to reconstruct what the book looked like, at every price level, after each event.

The data arrives as two paired files per stock per day. The message file has six columns: the time (seconds after midnight, to nanosecond precision), the event type (new limit order, cancellation, deletion, or execution), the order id, the size, the price (quoted in dollars multiplied by 10,000 so it stays a whole number), and the direction (buy or sell). The orderbook file lists, after each message, the price and size at each of the top levels on both sides. Message row k is the event that turns book row k−1 into book row k, so the two files together form a complete, self-checking history.

Free academic samples cover five large NASDAQ stocks — Apple, Amazon, Google, Intel, and Microsoft — for a single trading day, with roughly 300,000 to 600,000 events each; access to other stocks and dates needs an account. The dataset is widely used in market microstructure and machine learning research on high-frequency markets. The references at the end of this document point to the real dataset and its file-format documentation if you want to explore it. Our starter code does not download any of this — it simulates a stream with the same event types and shape, in memory, so you can study the collections under a realistic order-flow workload at any scale, with no internet access and nothing stored.

B.2 The idea: 50 GB processed, nothing stored
The program never writes a file and never reads one. In a tight loop it generates one event, applies it to the order book, and lets the event object be garbage-collected. The events are ephemeral; only the book’s state stays in memory. So, the amount of data processed can run into many tens of gigabytes, while the live memory is simply the size of the book. You drive the book until its live data reaches your target (about 50 GB) and measure it there. Generating on the fly rather than reading a file also helps keep the timing honest — a disk read inside a measured loop would dwarf the operation you are trying to time.

B.3 The collections inside it (the structures you are studying)
Two TreeMaps — one per side of the book, keyed by price so the best price is always at one end; each insert, cancel, and best-price lookup is O(log n).
An ArrayDeque at every price level — the FIFO queue of orders resting at that price, with O(1) work at both ends, giving price-time priority.
A HashMap from order id to order, so a cancellation finds its order in O(1) average instead of searching the book.
