Appendix C — Reading the machine’s resources from your own code (JDK 21)
Part C asks your program to report the machine’s resource use live, from inside the program, while the workload runs — not only from an external monitor. Java exposes this through the management beans in java.lang.management and the com.sun.management extension. Instruct Copilot to build a small background “monitor” thread that samples and prints these figures once a second.

In plain English:  your program watches itself. Every second it prints how much CPU it is using, how much memory is filled, how many threads are alive, and how hard the garbage collector is working, so you can see the resources climb as the order book grows.

C.1 What to report, and where each number comes from
Number of processors — Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors().
CPU load of your program (0 to 1; multiply by 100 for a percentage) — com.sun.management.OperatingSystemMXBean.getProcessCpuLoad(); the whole machine’s load is getCpuLoad().
Used heap memory — ManagementFactory.getMemoryMXBean().getHeapMemoryUsage().getUsed().
Total and free physical RAM — OperatingSystemMXBean.getTotalMemorySize() and getFreeMemorySize() (these are the JDK 21 names).
Live thread count — ManagementFactory.getThreadMXBean().getThreadCount().
Garbage-collection count and time — sum getCollectionCount() and getCollectionTime() over ManagementFactory.getGarbageCollectorMXBeans().
C.2 A monitor you can build on
Start this once, on a background (daemon) thread, before the workload begins. It prints a line a second until you stop the program.

import java.lang.management.*;

import com.sun.management.OperatingSystemMXBean;   // the com.sun version exposes CPU + RAM

 

OperatingSystemMXBean os = (OperatingSystemMXBean) ManagementFactory.getOperatingSystemMXBean();

MemoryMXBean memory      = ManagementFactory.getMemoryMXBean();

ThreadMXBean threadBean  = ManagementFactory.getThreadMXBean();

var gcBeans              = ManagementFactory.getGarbageCollectorMXBeans();

int cores = Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors();

 

Thread monitor = new Thread(() -> {

    try {

        while (running) {                                   // 'running' is a volatile boolean

            double cpuPct   = os.getProcessCpuLoad() * 100;  // CPU this JVM is using

            long usedHeapMB = memory.getHeapMemoryUsage().getUsed() >> 20;

            long freeRamMB  = os.getFreeMemorySize()  >> 20;

            long totalRamMB = os.getTotalMemorySize() >> 20;

            int  threads    = threadBean.getThreadCount();

            long gcCount = 0, gcTimeMs = 0;

            for (GarbageCollectorMXBean gc : gcBeans) {

                gcCount  += gc.getCollectionCount();

                gcTimeMs += gc.getCollectionTime();

            }

            System.out.printf("cpu=%.0f%%  heap=%,dMB  freeRAM=%,d/%,dMB  threads=%d  gc=%d (%,dms)%n",

                    cpuPct, usedHeapMB, freeRamMB, totalRamMB, threads, gcCount, gcTimeMs);

            Thread.sleep(1000);                              // sample once a second

        }

    } catch (InterruptedException e) { Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); }

});

monitor.setDaemon(true);

monitor.start();

C.3 Reading the numbers
CPU near 100% on one core means your single-threaded program is working flat out; to use more cores you would run several streams in parallel (Appendix B.7).
Used heap climbing toward your target is the book filling memory; if it plateaus while GC time shoots up, the collector is struggling to keep up — note where that happens.
Free RAM falling toward zero is the real ceiling; if it reaches zero the machine starts swapping to disk and everything slows to a crawl.
 